the behavior of primary voters? How quickly does the public learn about new candidates? Under what circumstances will primary success itself generate subsequent primary success? And what are the psychological processes underlying this dynamic tendency? Professor Bartels examines the likely consequences of some proposed alternatives to the current nominating process, including a regional primary system and a one-day national primary. Thus the work will be of interest to political activists, would-be reformers, and interested observers of the American political scene, as well as to students of public opinion, voting behavior, the news media, campaigns, and electoral institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxNomination. 0aPrimarieszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aBush, George.  aGallup Poll.  aGlenn, John.  aHouston Chronicle.  aIran hostage crisis.  aJanaskie, Paul.  aJohnston, Richard.  aKemp, Jack.  aKentucky Derby.  aLichtenstein, Sarah.  aOhio primary.  aOpus (penguin).  aSmith, Carolyn.  aSolid South.  aSuper Tuesday.  aTime magazine.  aVietnam war.  aWatergate.  aambiguity.  aapproval voting.  abandwagon.  abrokered convention.  acampaign effects.  acongressional caucuses.  acontagion.  aconventions.  adeathwatch coverage.  adefense spending.  adelegates.  aendogeneity of preferences.  aexpectations.  afeeling thermometer.  aforeign policy.  agovernment services.  ahorse race.  ainformation.  alabor unions.  aliberalism scores.  amedia use.  amomentum.  aname recognition.  anational primary.  anegative momentum.  anuclear power.  aparadox of voting.  apolitical activation.  aprojection.  areform.  aregional primaries.  athreshold mo